<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1060,1086]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</emphasis>
Thinly encrusting sponge, ≤ 
<quantity box="[673,752,1061,1087]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
thick, covered in short cylindrical or volcano shaped oscules that are around 
<quantity box="[324,389,1096,1123]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
high and 
<quantity box="[498,562,1097,1123]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Colour in life is lilac, with faint tan patches, oscules have a sharp, whitish margin; colour in ethanol is golden brown (
<figureCitation box="[721,844,1132,1159]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1526,1550]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-140@11.[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chalinula cf. molitba (De Laubenfels, 1949). MCCDRS9439: A. In situ. B. Deck photo of a small sample; C. Cross section of the choanosome. D. Oxeas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158079/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 5A–B</figureCitation>
). Texture is extremely soft, compressible, easily torn, surface is smooth to the touch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1204,1230]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Skeleton.</emphasis>
No ectosomal skeleton is present. The choanosomal skeleton is an isotropic reticulation of spicules that are completely encased in spongin. Most secondary tracts are unispicular, but occasionally they are 2–3 spicules in length. Free spicules are also present at low density in the choanosome (
<figureCitation box="[988,1077,1276,1303]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1526,1550]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-140@11.[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chalinula cf. molitba (De Laubenfels, 1949). MCCDRS9439: A. In situ. B. Deck photo of a small sample; C. Cross section of the choanosome. D. Oxeas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158079/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" box="[199,1163,1312,1339]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1312,1338]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Spicules.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[311,451,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Megascleres</emphasis>
—small oxeas; 113 (103–129) × 7 (5–9) µm (n = 20) (
<figureCitation box="[1060,1149,1312,1339]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1526,1550]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetId="figure-140@11.[151,1436,417,1503]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Chalinula cf. molitba (De Laubenfels, 1949). MCCDRS9439: A. In situ. B. Deck photo of a small sample; C. Cross section of the choanosome. D. Oxeas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158079/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1349,1375]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[371,469,1348,1374]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="(De Laubenfels, 1949)" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[506,969,1348,1375]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="molitba">
<emphasis box="[506,710,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chalinula molitba</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels, M. W." box="[724,960,1348,1375]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref38578" refString="De Laubenfels, M. W. (1949) Sponges of the Western Bahamas. American Museum Novitates, 1431, 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="1949">De Laubenfels, 1949</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
was described as a violet coloured, amorphous sponge with a reticulated skeleton of fibres that were around 30 µm in diameter and lightly cored by oxeas (100 × 2 µm). 
<bibRefCitation author="De Weerdt, W. H." box="[313,513,1420,1447]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 67" refId="ref38728" refString="De Weerdt, W. H. (2000) A monograph of the shallow-water Chalinidae (Porifera, Haplosclerida) of the Caribbean. Bueaufortia, 50 (1), 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="2000">De Weerdt (2000)</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the species after examining over 
<specimenCount box="[1022,1176,1420,1446]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">60 specimens</specimenCount>
, to include a wide variety of characteristics, ranging from: tubular to encrusting specimens; spongin- to spicule-dominated skeletons with scarce spongin; and strongyloxeas (45–99 × 0.5–2.6 µm) to oxeas (66–144 × 1.3–7 µm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[199,405,1528,1554]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="molitba">
<emphasis box="[199,405,1528,1554]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chalinula molitba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an eastern Atlantic species that has not been recorded from the eastern Pacific. However, the gross morphology, skeletal architecture and colour in life of our specimen fits well within the range of specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[183,304,1600,1627]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="molitba">
<emphasis box="[183,304,1600,1627]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">C. molitba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described in 
<bibRefCitation author="De Weerdt, W. H." box="[459,668,1600,1627]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 67" refId="ref38728" refString="De Weerdt, W. H. (2000) A monograph of the shallow-water Chalinidae (Porifera, Haplosclerida) of the Caribbean. Bueaufortia, 50 (1), 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="2000">De Weerdt (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. Given the wide range of characteristics in De Weerdt’s 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[1316,1437,1600,1627]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="molitba">
<emphasis box="[1316,1437,1600,1627]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">C. molitba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens, it is probable that they are not all the same species, but separation of these specimens, and ours, is likely to require re-examination using molecular tools. Molecular techniques such as sequencing mitochondrial DNA markers are becoming increasingly important for resolving accurate species boundaries (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Swierts, T. &amp; Peijnenburg, K. T. &amp; De Leeuw, C. A. &amp; Breeuwer, J. A. &amp; Cleary, D. F. &amp; De Voogd, N. J." box="[1211,1429,1708,1735]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="933 - 945" refId="ref42019" refString="Swierts, T., Peijnenburg, K. T., De Leeuw, C. A., Breeuwer, J. A., Cleary, D. F. &amp; De Voogd, N. J. (2017) Globally intertwined evolutionary history of giant barrel sponges. Coral Reefs, 36 (3), 933 - 945. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00338 - 017 - 1585 - 6" type="journal article" year="2017">
Swierts 
<emphasis box="[1304,1362,1708,1734]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
) and answering broad questions of whether the purported distribution of sponges across the 
<collectingCountry box="[1172,1261,1745,1771]" name="Panama" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Panama</collectingCountry>
isthmus is real. The Galápagos specimen has been given a tentative assignment to this species until further taxonomic work on the species is conducted.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Only one species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1868" box="[432,544,1852,1878]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,544,1852,1878]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chalinula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from the eastern Pacific: 
<taxonomicName authority="(De Laubenfels, 1930)" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1930" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="ecbasis">
<emphasis box="[1044,1246,1852,1878]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chalinula ecbasis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels, M. W." pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="24 - 29" refId="ref38325" refString="De Laubenfels, M. W. (1930) The Sponges of California. (Abstracts of dissertations for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy). Stanford University Bulletin, 5, 24 - 29." type="journal article" year="1930">De Laubenfels, 1930</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[287,404,1888,1914]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">California</collectingRegion>
. That species differs from the 
<collectingRegion box="[748,866,1888,1914]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Galápagos</collectingRegion>
specimen in that it is a digitate or ramose sponge, up to 
<quantity box="[215,284,1925,1951]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
high, with apical oscules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,952,2023]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<bibRefCitation author="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L." box="[199,504,1960,1989]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="257 - 264" refId="ref36862" refString="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L. (2008) A preliminary assessment of the invasiveness of the Indo-Pacific sponge Chalinula nematifera on coral communities from the tropical Eastern Pacific. Biological Invasions, 11 (2), 257 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10530 - 008 - 9230 - 5" type="journal article" year="2008">Ávila and Carballo (2008)</bibRefCitation>
reported that the western Pacific sponge, 
<taxonomicName authority="(De Laubenfels, 1954)" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1954" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="nematifera">
<emphasis box="[998,1242,1960,1987]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chalinula nematifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels, M. W." pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref38657" refString="De Laubenfels, M. W. (1954) Sponges of the west-central Pacific. Oregon State Monographs. Studies in Zoology, 7, 1 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6516" type="journal article" year="1954">De Laubenfels, 1954</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
had invaded the Mexican Pacific coast. Although no taxonomic description of the sponges are provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L." box="[151,445,151,179]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="257 - 264" refId="ref36862" refString="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L. (2008) A preliminary assessment of the invasiveness of the Indo-Pacific sponge Chalinula nematifera on coral communities from the tropical Eastern Pacific. Biological Invasions, 11 (2), 257 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10530 - 008 - 9230 - 5" type="journal article" year="2008">Ávila and Carballo (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, the images provided do not match with the species description of 
<emphasis box="[1178,1337,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1954" box="[1178,1333,151,177]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="nematifera">C. nematifera</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which is a thinly encrusting, vibrant mauve sponge with distinctive pale wavy ‘surface threads’, and very small oscules (oscules were not observed by De Laubenfels) (
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels, M. W." box="[654,886,222,249]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref38657" refString="De Laubenfels, M. W. (1954) Sponges of the west-central Pacific. Oregon State Monographs. Studies in Zoology, 7, 1 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6516" type="journal article" year="1954">De Laubenfels 1954</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="De Weerdt, W. H." box="[898,1086,223,249]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1867" refId="ref38764" refString="De Weerdt, W. H. (2002) Family Chalinidae Gray, 1867. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera: A Guide to the Classification of Sponges. Vol. 1. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York, New York, pp. 852 - 873. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 91" type="book chapter" year="2002">De Weerdt 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rossi, G. &amp; Montori, S. &amp; Cerrano, C. &amp; Calcinai, B." box="[1097,1291,222,249]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="143 - 148" refId="ref41388" refString="Rossi, G., Montori, S., Cerrano, C. &amp; Calcinai, B. (2015) The coral killing sponge Chalinula nematifera (Porifera: Haplosclerida) along the eastern coast of Sulawesi Island (Indonesia). Italian Journal of Zoology, 82 (1), 143 - 148. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 11250003.2014.994046" type="journal article" year="2015">
Rossi 
<emphasis box="[1166,1223,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast, the Mexican Pacific specimens (
<figureCitation box="[518,580,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1767,1791]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,417,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-100@5.[170,1416,417,1742]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sponge collection sites around the Galápagos Archipelago in this study." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158069/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig 1</figureCitation>
. in 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L." box="[624,932,259,287]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="257 - 264" refId="ref36862" refString="Avila, E. &amp; Carballo, J. L. (2008) A preliminary assessment of the invasiveness of the Indo-Pacific sponge Chalinula nematifera on coral communities from the tropical Eastern Pacific. Biological Invasions, 11 (2), 257 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10530 - 008 - 9230 - 5" type="journal article" year="2008">Ávila and Carballo (2008))</bibRefCitation>
were pale lilac in colour, possessed obvious volcano shaped oscules, and lacked the wavy surface threads. The external morphology of the Mexican Pacific specimens is similar to the 
<collectingRegion box="[451,569,331,357]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Galápagos</collectingRegion>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[717,870,331,357]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Chalinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="molitba">
<emphasis box="[717,736,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis box="[784,870,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">molitba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but further taxonomic work is required to confirm whether they are the same species.
</paragraph>
